{:ref/type :pattern, :ref/id "structural-law-family/coverage-ratchet"}, :evidence/author "ratchet/check-on-load!", :evidence/claim-type :observation, :evidence/id "e-8c149450-aacf-4d41-ad2f-491ddb8f787f"} {:evidence/body {:event "process-alert", :process-id "multi-watcher", :kind "missing", :severity "critical", :message "process not registered in CYDER", :details {}, :at "2026-07-04T18:46:33.681567230Z"}, :evidence/session-id "process-watchdog", :evidence/tags [:process-watchdog :infrastructure], :evidence/at "2026-07-04T18:46:33.681960797Z", :evidence/type :coordination, :evidence/subject {:ref/type :session, :ref/id "process-watchdog"}, :evidence/author "process-watchdog", :evidence/claim-type :observation, :evidence/id "e-9e7a6812-3d84-4a2c-a423-6cccbf73663c"} {:evidence/body {:event "chat-turn", :transport "emacs-claude-repl", :role "assistant", :turn-id "claude-16-turn-19", :text "Exactly — and that resolves D-frontier's direction while making the C3 contract two-tier. Recording it in the doc as the DERIVE opening note, since this is design input in your voice:Recorded as the DERIVE opening note. Your move does two things to the design at once:\n\n**D-frontier stops being a trilemma.** Instead of choosing between margin-zone, provisional placement, or hidden-until-re-embed, the answer is *approximate placement as a first-class citizen* — computed relative to the frozen embedding, cheap enough to run whenever a mission is born or changes. I've recorded three candidate mechanisms in cheapest-first order: a **relational centroid** (place the unmapped mission at the weighted center of its related *mapped* missions, relations read live from substrate-2 — this needs no feature pipeline and would work tonight; M-futon1b-port would land near its consumed-mission cluster), **feature-space kNN** (the textbook out-of-sample extension — needs one new verify row: which script and feature set generated the June-12 embed, and what role `efe-scopes.json` plays), and **text-embedding kNN** as the EFE-blind fallback via the existing BGE machinery.\n\n**And C3 becomes a two-tier contract**, which is more honest than either extreme: continuous cheap approximation (new missions appear on the map within a session of their birth) plus slow full re-embeds as *re-anchoring* — the moment approximate positions get retired to exact ones. The landscape drifts locally all the time and settles globally on the slow cadence, which matches your \"over time, the landscape would shift noticeably\" better than either pure-live or pure-batch would.\n\nOne binding requirement I attached to all three mechanisms, from the HEAD's own discipline: approximate placements must render *visibly distinct* from embedded ones — dashed ring versus solid, with provenance (`:placement :approximate`, method, as-of) carried in the data. The frontier stays legible as frontier; nobody mistakes a guess for a measurement.\n\nThe doc now has everything DERIVE proper needs: the join shape, the two-tier cadence, three placement mechanisms awaiting selection (with one verify row on the feature pipeline), and the honesty constraint. That's a natural handoff point for a fresh session — or, given how the last two missions have gone, a rather well-shaped first dispatch for whoever ends up owning the build.", :mission-id "M-custom-harness", :clocked-mission "M-custom-harness", :clocked-target "M-custom-harness"}, :evidence/session-id "a0fffb83-80b1-493f-9ebe-ebf5f9a2197b", :evidence/tags [:claude :chat :turn :assistant], :evidence/at "2026-07-04T18:46:21.753737793Z", :evidence/type :coordination, :evidence/subject {:ref/type :session, :ref/id "a0fffb83-80b1-493f-9ebe-ebf5f9a2197b"}, :evidence/author "claude-16", :evidence/claim-type :observation, :evidence/id "e-6a7df0d5-ff25-4666-8213-44c6dc1f7063"} {:evidence/body {"warm" true, "result-preview" "Exactly — and that resolves D-frontier's direction while making the C3 contract two-tier. Recording it in the doc as the DERIVE opening note, s