on as a trim candidate** — a feature (`scan-for-completion`) that's dead-weight *and* self-worsening, flagged to trim and coalesce into \"maintained done-set.\" So the constellation's trim/coalesce lens catches *real* smells, not just tidiness — which is a good sign the design is pointed at something true.\n\nWant me to fold this into `feature-constellation-design-note.md` — a short section: *\"the collapse principle generalizes — features by k, evidence by recency, state by maintained projection; anything reached only by full materialization is a trim candidate\"*? It's the same idea and the note is its natural home."}, :evidence/session-id "23b70755-aaf1-4cc7-8a4a-39db7645bcba", :evidence/tags [:claude :chat :turn :assistant], :evidence/at "2026-07-04T18:27:52.395655840Z", :evidence/type :coordination, :evidence/subject {:ref/type :session, :ref/id "23b70755-aaf1-4cc7-8a4a-39db7645bcba"}, :evidence/author "claude-10", :evidence/claim-type :observation, :evidence/id "e-75a377e7-6b30-43b2-953d-632b658ca15c"} {:evidence/body {"warm" true, "result-preview" "Yes — it's the *same move on a different substrate*, and I think that's the real unifying thread of today.\n\nThe feature constellation says: never hold the whole feature graph expanded; work with a **bounded projection at level k** (leaves peeled, retracted toward the core). The evidence discipline s", "event" "invoke-complete", "agent-id" "claude-10", "at" "2026-07-04T18:27:48.916253608Z"}, :evidence/session-id "23b70755-aaf1-4cc7-8a4a-39db7645bcba", :evidence/tags [:invoke :dev :claude-10 :invoke-complete], :evidence/at "2026-07-04T18:27:48.916878410Z", :evidence/type :coordination, :evidence/subject {:ref/type :agent, :ref/id "claude-10"}, :evidence/author "claude-10", :evidence/claim-type :step, :evidence/id "e-c4e4eb56-b158-40ef-8017-c7b49299a362"} {:evidence/body {"event" "context-retrieval", "agent-id" "claude-16", "at" "2026-07-04T18:27:37.304591603Z", "turn" 29, "query" "Yes, so here's the HEAD:  One of t