clocked yet is that *today's work accidentally built the data layer for it*.\n\n**The live-agents half is nearly free now.** For the map to show \"which agents are running around,\" it needs three feeds, and all three exist as of tonight: the registry knows who's alive and invoking; the invoke-jobs ledger streams what each one is *doing* right now (the same events your follow-mode renders — \"using search\", tool previews); and — the piece I only noticed while wiring zai-9 this evening — `clock-dispatch!` already **persists agent→mission edges as hyperedges in substrate-2** when an agent clocks in. Agent position on the mission map isn't a visualization trick to be invented; it's a query over edges that are already being written. The ship-shaped gap is exactly your cursor: and M-emacs-cursor-peripheral's streaming code (already proven reusable once, for the websocket work) maps a cursor to a *file*, and the enrichment layer maps files to *missions* — so \"where is Joe\" composes out of two finished pieces. The operator becomes one more embodied agent on the same field, which is your own operator-not-sovereign principle made visible: not a god's-eye view over the ants, but a rocket among them.\n\n**The Ants correspondence is exact, and it has a name.** What makes the AIF Ants map work isn't the food — it's stigmergy: agents modify the field that guides them. That's precisely what mission work does to the EFE landscape. An agent fixes a mission → its EFE drops → the field reshapes → attention flows elsewhere. That's the niche-construction reading from M-aif2 rendered literally: the landscape shift *is* the record of collective work, and the coordination edges (who belled whom, the trails `recent_coordination` reads) are the pheromones. Your framing also quietly resolves the badge question you opened with: if badges/stars are field-features rather than requirements — things that make the landscape legible, not things the WM needs to run — that's consistent with the ove