ed-problem-ids`** (apm): fetch all → filter to `:ct-extraction`/`:apm-proof` + `:workflow-complete`/`:kick-complete` → return the **set of already-processed IDs**. That's **completion-dedup** — \"what's already done so I don't redo it.\"\n- **`tickle-status`**: fetch all → filter to `:orchestrate` → compute uptime/kick/completion counts. **Status summary.**\n\nSo it's **not** \"recent adjacent evidence\" — it's **all-time, tag-filtered completion/status tracking**. Which means a *recency* bound would be **wrong** (an old completion still counts — miss it and you re-process done work). But notice: **they already filter by tag right after fetching everything.** The fix is to push that tag filter *into* the query — which the backend supports (`:query/tags` → datalog membership → bounded, ~7ms) — for **identical results, cheaply.** Let me apply that:3 edits applied, clj-kondo clean (the 1 warning is a pre-existing redefined-var at line 61, not my line 834). Let me check-parens and see whether these nss are safe to live-reload (no stateful top-level forms):check-parens OK; the only top-level forms are pure `def`-constants (paths, tag-sets) — no atoms/defonce, so these agent nss are safe to reload. Let me commit and apply live:Committed (`7774a83`) + all 3 nss reloaded live (`:reloaded`). Let me confirm the log is quiet now — both count and query timeouts:Count timeouts are **gone** (0), `/health` is 18ms. But **query timeouts persist (10)** — either stale in-flight queries draining post-reload, or callers I missed. Let me check both: all query callers, and whether these are pre- or post-reload:Those query-timeouts at lines 93-98 are **after** the last invoke-trace (17:58) — so **post-reload, still happening**. My 3-caller fix didn't stop them, meaning either my reload didn't take or there's another `{}` caller. The params tell us who — let me see them un-stripped:I need to step back and be honest about what this is showing, rather than keep whacking callers:\n\nThe params reveal the real situation:\n- **Count timeouts: gone. Attach: works.** — the actual problem you hit is fixed.\n- **But `query timed out` has multiple sources**, and one is telling: `params={:query/type :coordination, :query/since \"2026-06-27\", :query/limit 2000}` — that query is **already bounded** (typed, time-windowed, capped at 2000) and it **still times out.** That means the issue is no longer individual unbounded callers — **the store itself is too slow**, even for reasonable bounded queries. There are ~6 more `{}` callers and this coordination one; patching them one by one isn't converging.\n\n## Honest reassessment\n\nI fixed the two things that mattered (the count flood + attach), plus three genuinely-unbounded query callers (`7774a83`). But the coordination query timing out **despite** a type+since+limit tells me the root is **store size/performance**, not caller hygiene — the evidence store has grown large enough that broad-ish scans blow 15s regardless. That's the deeper futon1a#5 issue, and it's **systemic, not a live-patch**.\n\nThe right fix at that level is store-side, and it connects to work already in the stack:\n- **Compaction/pruning** — drop or archive old ephemeral evidence (there's already a `compact` path in `store.clj`, and we built the gated erase path earlier this session). Shrinking the hot store is what makes queries fast again.\n- and/or a **maintained index / faster count**, per #5.\n\nSo my recommendation: **stop the caller whack-a-mole here.** The wins are banked (attach + count). Let me capture this systemic finding on #5 and treat \"the evidence store has outgrown its query budget → compact/prune it\" as the real work item — which is a scoped mission (using the erase/compact machinery), not more live edits. \n\nWant me to (a) write that up on #5 and pause, (b) scope the store-compaction as its own excursion (like we did for the constellation), or (c) keep patching the remaining query callers anyway? My honest read is (a)+(b) — the callers are a symptom; the store size is the disease."}, :evidence/session-id "23b70755-aaf1-4cc7-8a4a-39db7645bcba", :evidence/tags [:claude :chat :turn :assistant], :evidence/at "2026-07-04T18:08:31.658651608Z", :evidence/type :coordination, :evidence/subject {:ref/type :session, :ref/id "23b70755-aaf1-4cc7-8a4a-39db7645bcba"}, :evidence/author "claude-10", :evidence/claim-type :observation, :evidence/id "e-4e202587-1822-4607-a656-b11c8f4637c0"} {:evidence/body {"warm" true, "result-preview" "That's the structural echo of zai-9's driving turn — already reviewed and answered in-thread. Two pieces of my own follow-through to land while things are quiet: the formal flag to Joe, and my committed Q1 deliverable (the slice export), so the next driving turn is fully unblocked. Producing the exp", "mission-id" "M-custom-harness", "clocked-mission" "M-custom-harness", "auto-clock-witness" {:rule "agent-edit-activity", :source "agent-tool-edit", :file "/home/joe/code/futon2/holes/M-custom-harness.md", :edit-count 3, :window-seconds 600, :old-target "no mission", :new-target "M-custom-harness"}, "event" "invoke-complete", "agent-id" "claude-16", "at" "2026-07-04T18:08:31.480980550Z"}, :evidence/session-id "a0fffb83-80b1-493f-9ebe-ebf5f9a2197b", :evidence/tags [:invoke :dev :claude-16 :invoke-complete], :evidence/at "2026-07-04T18:08:31.481263134Z", :evidence/type :coordination, :evidence/subject {:ref/type :agent, :ref/id "claude-16"}, :evidence/author "claude-16", :evidence/claim-type :step, :evidence/id "e-541208ef-caca-42bf-8ee1-7d132a999555"} {:evidence/body {"warm" true, "result-preview" "Exactly right — and that reframes it perfectly: if it were just N, we'd get it cheaply; the fetch-all is (probably) so agents can read *recent adjacent* evidence. Let me confirm that's what these three actually do with the entries — because if so, \"recent\" is both the cheap *and* the semantically-co", "event" "invoke-complete", "agent-id" "claude-10", "at" "2026-07-04T18:08:28.248